65-66. The ancient loom was vertical and the tela or warp hung down from the upper cross bearn. Sinkere (pondera, Sen. Epist. 90, 20, here lateres because made of balred clay) were attached to the several threads to keep them taut and equidistant. Every time a thread of the woof was driven horne by the comb or ‘lay' (pecten, ‘wool’ is subtemen) the lateres of course rattled against each other, hence ‘applauso tela sonat latere! For a com· plete description of the process see Ovid‚ Met. 6, 54.
